Nangong (surname)|Nangong]]}} || {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Mo (Chinese surname)|\u58a8]]|[[Mo (Chinese surname)|Mo]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Ha (Chinese surname)#Surnames|\u54c8]]|[[Ha (Chinese surname)#Surnames|Ha]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Qiao (surname)|\u8b59]]|[[Qiao (surname)|Qiao]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Da (surname)|\u7b2a]]|[[Da (surname)|Da]]}} || {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Nian (surname)|\u5e74]]|[[Nian (surname)|Nian]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Ai (surname)|\u611b]]|[[Ai (surname)|Ai]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Yang (\u967d)|\u967d]]|[[Yang (\u967d)|Yang]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Tong (surname)|\u4f5f]]|[[Tong (surname)|Tong]]}}\n|-\n| {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Diwu|\u7b2c\u4e94]]|[[Diwu]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Yan (surname)|\u8a00]]|[[Yan (surname)|Yan]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Fu (surname)|\u798f]]|[[Fu (surname)|Fu]]}} || {{Ruby-zh-p|\u767e|B\u01cei}} {{Ruby-zh-p|\u5bb6|ji\u0101}} {{Ruby-zh-p|\u59d3|x\u00ecng}} {{Ruby-zh-p|\u7d42|zh\u014dng}}<ref>The last four-character line means \"thus ends the ''Hundred Family Surnames''.\" It is not intended to contain surnames.</ref>\n|}\n</center>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chinese surname|Chinese surnames]]\n* [[List of common Chinese surnames]]\n* ''[[Seek for Surname History]]''\n* ''[[Three Character Classic]]''\n* ''[[Thousand Character Classic]]''\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book |last = Rawski |first = Evelyn Sakakida |year = 1979 |title = Education and Popular Literacy in Ch'ing China |publisher = University of Michigan Press| location = Ann Arbor |isbn = 0-472-08753-3|ref = harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikisourcelang|zh|\u767e\u5bb6\u59d3|Hundred Family Surnames}}\n* {{librivox book | title=Hundred Surnames}} in mandarin\n\n{{Confucian texts}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese classic texts]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language surnames|*Hundred Family Surnames]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|c=\u767e\u5bb6\u59d3\n|p=B\u01ceiji\u0101 X\u00ecng\n|showflag=p\n|gr=Baejia Shinq\n|mi={{IPAc-cmn|b|ai|3|.|j|ya|1|-|x|ing|4}}\n|w=Pai<sup>3</sup> Chia<sup>1</sup> Hsing<sup>4</sup>\n|myr=B\u01ceijy\u0101 Sy\u00ecng\n|bpmf=\u3105\u311e\u02c7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\u3110\u3127\u311a&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\u3112\u3127\u3125\u02cb\n|j=baak3 gaa1 sing3\n|y=Baakg\u0101 Sing\n}}{{Use American English|date = January 2019}}\n{{Short description|Classic composition of common surnames in China's Song Dynasty}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = January 2019}}\n{{Ruby notice}}\n\nThe '''''Hundred Family Surnames''''' is a classic [[Chinese language|Chinese]] text composed of common [[Chinese surname]]s. The book was composed in the early [[Song dynasty]].<ref name=\"KS\">K. S. Tom. [1989] (1989). Echoes from Old China: Life, Legends and Lore of the Middle Kingdom. [[University of Hawaii Press]]. {{ISBN|0-8248-1285-9}}.</ref>  It originally contained 411 surnames, and was later expanded to 504.{{when|date=March 2020}}<ref name=\"KS\" /> Of these, 444 are single-character surnames, and 60 are [[Chinese compound surname|double-character surnames]].  About 800 names have been derived from the original ones.<ref>Chen, Janey. [1992] (1992). A Practical English-Chinese Pronouncing Dictionary. Tuttle Publishing. {{ISBN|0-8048-1877-0}}</ref>\n\nIn the dynasties following the Song, the ''[[Three Character Classic]]'', the ''Hundred Family Surnames'', and ''[[Thousand Character Classic]]'' came to be known as ''San Bai Qian'' (Three, Hundred, Thousand), from the first character in their titles.  They were the almost universal introductory literary texts for students, almost exclusively boys, from elite backgrounds and even for a number of ordinary villagers.  Each was available in many versions, printed cheaply, and available to all since they did not become superseded. When a student had memorized all three, he had a knowledge of roughly 2,000 characters. Since Chinese did not use an alphabet, this was an effective, though time-consuming, way of giving a \"crash course\" in character recognition before going on to understanding texts and writing characters.{{sfnp|Rawski|1979|pp=46\u201348}}\n\nThe ''Hundred Family Surnames'' was translated into [[Manchu language|Manchu]] as {{MongolUnicode|\u182a\u185d \u1864\u1873\u1836\u1820 \u1830\u1873\u1829}} (Wylie: Pe giya sing, [[Transliterations of Manchu|M\u00f6llendorff]]: Be giya sing).\n\n==Form==\nThe work is a rhyming poem in lines of eight characters. The surnames are not listed in order of commonality. According to Song dynasty scholar Wang Mingqing (\u738b\u660e\u6e05), the first four surnames listed represent the most important families in the empire at the time:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/focus/2006-03/05/content_4232963.htm |script-title=zh:\"\u767e\u5bb6\u59d3\"\u6392\u5217\u7ec8\u6709\u5e8f \u59d3\u6c0f\u6587\u5316\u6709\u4f55\u5185\u6db5\uff1f |date=2006-03-05 |publisher=Xinhua |language=Chinese |accessdate=2014-11-07}}</ref>\n\n*1st: [[Zhao (surname)|Zhao]] ({{lang|zh-hant|\u8d99}}) is the surname of the [[Song dynasty]] emperors.\n*2nd: [[Qian (surname)|Qian]] ({{lang|zh-hant|\u9322}}) is the surname of the kings of [[Wuyue]].\n*3rd: [[Sun (surname)|Sun]] ({{lang|zh-hant|\u5b6b}}) is the surname of the queen of Wuyue.\n*4th: [[Li (surname \u674e)|Li]] ({{lang|zh-hant|\u674e}}) is the surname of the kings of [[Southern Tang]].\n\nThe next four, [[Zhou (surname)|Zhou \u5468]], [[Wu (surname)|Wu \u5433]], [[Zheng (surname)|Zheng \u912d]], and [[Wang (surname)|Wang \u738b]], were the surnames of the other wives of [[Qian Chu]], the last king of Wuyue.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chinanews.com/cul/2014/09-03/6556695.shtml |script-title=zh:\u94b1\u6c0f\u4fee\"\u767e\u5bb6\u59d3\"\u5c06\u94b1\u59d3\u6392\u7b2c2\u4f4d \u94b1\u738b\u5983\u5b50\u59d3\u6c0f\u9760\u524d |date=2014-09-03 |author=Chen Danning |publisher=China News |language=Chinese |accessdate=2014-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==Complete text==\nThis text is written in [[Traditional Chinese]]. Note that several of these characters may link to the same article. The last four-character line means \"thus ends the ''Hundred Family Surnames''.\" It is not intended to contain surnames\n<center>\n{|style=\"text-align:center\"\n| {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Zhao (surname)|\u8d99]]|[[Zhao (surname)|Zhao]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Qian (surname)|\u9322]]|[[Qian (surname)|Qian]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Sun (surname)|\u5b6b]]|[[Sun (surname)|Sun]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Li (surname \u674e)|\u674e]]|[[Li (surname \u674e)|Li]]}} || {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Zhou (surname)|\u5468]]|[[Zhou (surname)|Zhou]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Wu (surname)|\u5433]]|[[Wu (surname)|Wu]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Zheng (surname)|\u912d]]|[[Zheng (surname)|Zheng]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Wang (surname)|\u738b]]|[[Wang (surname)|Wang]]}} || {{Ruby-zh-p|[[F\u00e9ng (surname)|\u99ae]]|[[F\u00e9ng (surname)|Feng]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Chen (surname)|\u9673]]|[[Chen (surname)|Chen]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Chu (Chinese surname)|\u891a]]|[[Chu (Chinese surname)|Chu]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Wei (surname)|\u885b]]|[[Wei (surname)|Wei]]}} || {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Ji\u01ceng (surname)|\u8523]]|[[Ji\u01ceng (surname)|Jiang]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Sh\u011bn (surname)|\u6c88]]|[[Sh\u011bn (surname)|Shen]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Han (Chinese surname)|\u97d3]]|[[Han (Chinese surname)|Han]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Yang (surname)|\u694a]]|[[Yang (surname)|Yang]]}}\n|-\n| {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Zhu (surname)|\u6731]]|[[Zhu (surname)|Zhu]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Qin (surname)|\u79e6]]|[[Qin (surname)|Qin]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[You (surname)|\u5c24]]|[[You (surname)|You]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[X\u01d4 (surname)|\u8a31]]|[[X\u01d4 (surname)|Xu]]}} || {{Ruby-zh-p|[[He (surname)|\u4f55]]|[[He (surname)|He]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[L\u00fc (surname)|\u5442]]|[[L\u00fc (surname)|L\u00fc]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Shi (surname)|\u65bd]]|[[Shi (surname)|Shi]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Zhang (surname)|\u5f35]]|[[Zhang (surname)|Zhang]]}} || {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Kong (surname)|\u5b54]]|[[Kong (surname)|Kong]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Cao (Chinese surname)|\u66f9]]|[[Cao (Chinese surname)|Cao]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Yan (surname)|\u56b4]]|[[Yan (surname)|Yan]]}} {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Hua (surname)|\u83ef]]|[[Hua (surname)|Hua]]}} || {{Ruby-zh-p|[[Jin (Chi